# webskop — React & file conventions

## One folder per component

- Put each UI component in its own directory under `src/components/`.
- **Folder name**: **lowercase, words separated with hyphens** (kebab-case only — no spaces or PascalCase), e.g. `desktop`, `desktop-folder`, `task-bar`.
- Example: `src/components/desktop/Desktop.tsx` + `src/components/desktop/desktop.scss`.

## Files in each component folder

- **TSX**: Name the file after the component in PascalCase, e.g. `Desktop.tsx` (not a generic `component.tsx`).
- **SCSS**: One stylesheet per component, **`.scss` extension**, **lowercase**; **use underscores (`_`) to separate words** in the filename — not hyphens. Examples: `desktop.scss` (single word), `desktop_folder.scss` (matches folder `desktop-folder`).
- Import from the TSX file: `import './desktop.scss'` or `import './desktop_folder.scss'`.

## Design system & SCSS (required)

- **Single global entry**: `src/index.scss` imports `src/core/ui/global.scss` once. **Do not** import `global.scss` again from component SCSS files (duplicates CSS output).
- **Global bundle** (`src/core/ui/global.scss`) pulls in, in order: **global colors** (`style/color/_global-colors.scss`), **theme** (`style/color/_theme.scss`), **measure** (`_measure.scss`), **align** (`_align.scss`), **common** (`_common.scss`), **fonts** (`typography/_fonts.scss`), **typography utilities** (`typography/_typography.scss`). Extend `global.scss` when new shared UI layers are added.
- **Colors**: Prefer palette and semantic tokens — `var(--gray-800)`, `var(--white)`, `var(--text-main)` inside `.light-theme`, etc. — from those files. Avoid ad hoc hex values in component styles when an existing token fits.
- **Typography & color in markup**: Use the existing utility classes (`typography--body`, `typography--subhead-semibold`, `color--text-main`, `is-centered-text`, …) on elements alongside BEM classes instead of re-specifying font size, weight, or theme text colors in component SCSS when a utility exists.
- **Layout helpers**: Reuse utilities from `_align.scss` / `_common.scss` (`is-centered`, `hide-on-sm`, …) when they match the need.
- **Theme hook**: The app shell uses **`class="light-theme"`** on `<body>` (see `index.html`) so semantic theme variables resolve.
- Component SCSS should emphasize **structure, spacing, and states** unique to that component; tokens and typography come from the globals above.

## React style

- Use **function components only** (no class components).
- Use the **`function` keyword by default** for named functions, helpers, and exported declarations.
- Do **not** use arrow functions for component declarations or general named helpers.
- Exception: arrow functions are allowed (and preferred when concise) for short inline callbacks required by APIs such as `map`, `filter`, `reduce`, `find`, event listeners, and React state updater functions like `setState(prev => …)`.

```tsx
// ✅ Good
export function Desktop() {
  return <div className="desktop">…</div>
}

// ❌ Avoid
export const Desktop = () => { … }
```

- For named helpers in the same file, prefer `function helperName() {}` over `const helperName = () => {}` (reserve arrow functions for the inline callback/state-updater exception above).

## JSX spacing

- Keep exactly **one space** between JSX siblings when they appear on the same line (e.g. `</Foo> <Bar />`), not `</Foo><Bar />` or with multiple spaces.

## Curly braces for control flow

- Always use curly braces for control-flow blocks (especially `if`/`else`), even when the block contains a single statement. Never write `if (cond) return value` without `{ ... }`.

Example (see `src/App.tsx` around the `if (folder.id !== openFolderId)` logic):

```tsx
if (folder.id !== openFolderId){
  return folder
}
```

## Props destructuring (All components)

- In React components, destructure props in the function parameter list (e.g. `function Component({ a, b }: PropsType)`).
- Do not keep a `props` parameter and then reference `props.*` throughout the component body.
